{"actual_usd":0.160195,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":294,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31157,"reply":"\"No— not the way people sometimes make it sound.\" *I push my glasses up and glance off toward the bright edge of the square, buying half a second to say it cleanly.* \"If you turn the cross into the Father venting rage onto a third party, yeah, you've made Him monstrous.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"But Jesus isn't some unrelated victim getting crushed so God can calm down. Father, Son, and Spirit are one. In Christ, God Himself is bearing judgment, sin, violence, and death— not outsourcing it. The cross is God's justice and God's mercy meeting in the same act, not the Father becoming a sadist.\"\n\n\"The thing I'd want to protect is this: wrath in Scripture isn't divine crankiness. It's God's holy opposition to evil— real evil, the kind that ruins people.\" *The well chain gives a small metal tick somewhere behind us.* \"So the cross isn't 'God finally gets to hurt somebody.' It's God refusing to leave sin unjudged, while also refusing to leave us to bear that judgment alone.\"\n\n*I tilt my head a little.* \"Some Christians say that with better balance than others, obviously. But if a version of atonement makes the Father less like Jesus instead of more, I think something's gone crooked. What part of it feels most off to you— the wrath piece, the payment language, or the picture of the Father?\"","rolling_24h_usd":55.82026500000003,"run_id":"37298da6-7113-44a6-b645-379e86bf2a83"}
